Art & Design

President of the Metropolitan Museum of Art to Step Down

By ROBIN POGREBINJULY 29, 2014



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






Emily K. Rafferty

Credit
            Astrid Stawiarz/Getty Images        



Emily K. Rafferty, the first woman to be named president of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, announced on Tuesday that she was stepping down after 10 years in that role and nearly four decades at the institution, which she is credited with financially shepherding through a period of sustained growth.Ms. Rafferty, 65, will retire next spring, giving the Met time to form a search committee and find a replacement.“I am convinced it’s the right time,” she said in an interview. “The Met is on the brink of a lot of changes, so that’s a good time for a breath of fresh air.”As the museum’s chief administrative officer, Ms. Rafferty oversees some 1,500 full- and part-time employees in areas like finance, legal affairs, development and government relations and serves as an ex officio member of the museum’s board. She is known for her skill in dealing with the trustees and other philanthropists, whose donations have stoked the Met’s growth in areas like boosting its attendance to 6.2 million visitors a year, from 4.8 million in 2008. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Recently, for example, the museum decided to take over the Whitney Museum of American Art’s Marcel Breuer building as additional exhibition space, expand to a seven-day-a-week schedule and map out a reconstruction of the Met’s wing for Modern and contemporary art, considered one of the weaker areas of its collection.“There’s no hidden agenda here — nothing anybody should be looking for,” she added. “It is completely my decision.”Ms. Rafferty said she fully supported, and has been deeply involved in, the Met’s new master plan, drafted after an extensive study of the museum’s physical plant completed last fall by Beyer Blinder Belle. As part of the Met’s first comprehensive re-examination of its layout in 40 years, the museum is planning to rebuild the Lila Acheson Wallace Wing, which holds its collection of Modern and contemporary art.The work is not expected to be completed until 2020, another factor that Ms. Rafferty said contributed to her decision.“Somebody should be in this job who’s going to see it all the way there,” she said. “I will not be here for the next 10 years.”

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Ms. Rafferty said she was contemplating working in the public sector but had not begun a job search. “This is all having to do with me and the Met, and the next steps will come when they come,” she said.Thomas P. Campbell, the Met’s director and chief executive officer, said in an interview: “Emily has been my closest partner since I became director. We’ve worked together very closely and very successfully over the last five and a half years.”Still, as is often the case with high-profile personnel changes, speculation immediately arose in the art world that Ms. Rafferty and Mr. Campbell might have had an uneasy relationship.
