But while acknowledging that rumors were inevitable, Ms. Rafferty and Mr. Campbell both said their relationship had been fully collegial. “She combines leadership and friendship at the highest level,” Mr. Campbell said. “Any success that I have enjoyed in leading this museum would simply not have been possible without her at my side.”Ms. Rafferty said she and Mr. Campbell had “partnered well” during the leadership transition that followed the departure of Philippe de Montebello, who led the Met for 31 years before resigning at the end of 2008. “I have enjoyed every minute working with him,” she said.Mr. Campbell said he appreciated Ms. Rafferty’s decision to leave “before we get embroiled in all these new projects.”“In a sense, this is Emily perhaps at her best,” he said, “thinking about the institution, thinking about the future.”Ms. Rafferty is widely described as a steadying force in the often tumultuous New York arts world, in which high-powered institutions vie for public and private dollars. Tom Finkelpearl, who recently became the city’s cultural affairs commissioner, said that the first phone call he fielded after assuming his post was from Ms. Rafferty. “She’s got this incredibly calm nature,” he said.Mr. de Montebello described Ms. Rafferty as “an invaluable partner” who “was really devoted to the Met.”

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

After arriving in 1976 as an administrator in the development department, Ms. Rafferty rose to the post of vice president in charge of development and membership and later became senior vice president for external affairs.Ms. Rafferty has also served since 2008 as the chairwoman of NYC & Company, the city’s tourism and marketing agency, and is on the board of the National September 11 Memorial & Museum. In 2011 she was named to the board of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, and she became its chairwoman in 2012.While she is retiring from the Met, Ms. Rafferty said, there is no Florida golf course in her immediate future. Precisely what comes next remains to be seen, however.“You will see me out there,” she said. “I just don’t know quite where that will be.”

 Correction: July 31, 2014  
An article on Wednesday about an announcement by Emily K. Rafferty, president of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, that she will retire next spring misstated the day of the announcement and of the ensuing speculation in the art world about her working relationship with Thomas P. Campbell, the Met’s director and chief executive. They occurred Tuesday, not Wednesday. 


